        {
          "id": 514144,
          "key": "29d25468-2ac0-4a9f-ac21-962c4765f498",
          "title": "Linear Combination and Span",
          "semantic_type": "Concept",
          "is_public": true,
          "user_state": {
            "node_key": "29d25468-2ac0-4a9f-ac21-962c4765f498",
            "completed_at": null,
            "last_viewed_at": null,
            "unstructured": null
          },
          "resources": null,
          "atoms": [
            {
              "id": 518717,
              "key": "235a2dfc-cc19-4661-9b0c-c457d14fce2b",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "# Linear Combination and Span- Theoretical Definitions",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527318,
              "key": "88576013-30e0-4901-ada3-0dc0366a4c49",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "In general terms, the simple definition of a **linear combination** is a multiplication of a scalar to a variable  and addition of those terms.\n\nFor example:\n\nIf \n<span class=\"mathquill\">x</span>, <span class=\"mathquill\">y</span> and <span class=\"mathquill\">z</span> are variables,\n\n and <span class=\"mathquill\">a_1</span>, <span class=\"mathquill\">a_2</span> and <span class=\"mathquill\">a_3</span> are scalars, \n\nthe following equations will be a linear combination:\n\n<span class=\"mathquill\">v=a_1x+a_2y+a_3z</span>\n\n_Equation 6_\n\n\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527320,
              "key": "fc7ebcbf-8939-4a15-9fa8-c8726673365d",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "Let's now put it into the Linear Algebra context. \n\nOur variables will now be vectors: <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{x}</span>, <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{y}</span> and <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{z}</span> are variables. \n\nThe scalars can remain the same:\n<span class=\"mathquill\">a_1</span>, <span class=\"mathquill\">a_2</span> and <span class=\"mathquill\">a_3</span>.\n\nA linear combination of a scalar by a vector will be a new vector:\n\n<span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v}=a_1\\vec{x}+a_2\\vec{y}+a_3\\vec{z}</span> \n\n_Equation 7_\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527322,
              "key": "86ee6315-f6d4-40c9-8450-5d077965e09e",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "ImageAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "url": "https://video.udacity-data.com/topher/2018/January/5a6f7b0b_screen-shot-2018-01-29-at-11.49.47-am/screen-shot-2018-01-29-at-11.49.47-am.png",
              "non_google_url": "https://s3.cn-north-1.amazonaws.com.cn/u-img/86ee6315-f6d4-40c9-8450-5d077965e09e",
              "caption": "",
              "alt": "",
              "width": 300,
              "height": 120,
              "instructor_notes": null
            },
            {
              "id": 527321,
              "key": "7b7d38ec-de88-4cc0-b999-3182b2b4e7c2",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "A linear combination can be of a single addition, or (as shown in equations 4 above) of any number of additions.\n\nThe general notation of a vector by a scalar linear combination will be:\n\n<span class=\"mathquill\">\\sum_{1}^{n}a_i\\vec{v_i}</span> \n\n_Equation 8_",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527323,
              "key": "5373ac63-ddd3-4ab6-b40b-4a30bdb72cfe",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "What is the **Span**?",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527324,
              "key": "200850e5-d223-4367-b29b-90dff112a763",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "ImageAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "url": "https://video.udacity-data.com/topher/2018/January/5a6f7b75_screen-shot-2018-01-29-at-11.51.35-am/screen-shot-2018-01-29-at-11.51.35-am.png",
              "non_google_url": "https://s3.cn-north-1.amazonaws.com.cn/u-img/200850e5-d223-4367-b29b-90dff112a763",
              "caption": "",
              "alt": "",
              "width": 300,
              "height": 100,
              "instructor_notes": null
            },
            {
              "id": 527404,
              "key": "3ededc3b-0097-43c0-bae2-c82031d594e7",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "If <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_1}, \\vec{v_2},....., \\vec{v_n}\\in \\mathbb{R} </span> \nthen\n\nthe **Span** of those vectors (sometimes also referred to as the Linear Span) is the set of all possible linear combinations of those vectors.\n\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527405,
              "key": "14295a97-1744-4411-be69-240216e6bf4b",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "Mathematically, the span of the set of vectors  <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_1}, \\vec{v_2},....., \\vec{v_n}</span> is written as:\n\n <span class=\"mathquill\">Sp(\\vec{v_1}, \\vec{v_2},....., \\vec{v_n})</span> \n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527408,
              "key": "15f884d2-b153-4cdb-87a9-9c1bee619065",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "For example:\n\nThe three following vectors:  <span class=\"mathquill\">\n\\vec{v_1}=\\begin{bmatrix} \n1\n\\\\0\n\\\\0\n\\end{bmatrix}</span> , <span class=\"mathquill\">\n\\vec{v_2}=\\begin{bmatrix} \n0\n\\\\1\n\\\\0\n\\end{bmatrix}</span>  and <span class=\"mathquill\">\n\\vec{v_3}=\\begin{bmatrix} \n0\n\\\\0\n\\\\1\n\\end{bmatrix}</span>  span any vector in <span class=\"mathquill\">\n\\mathbb{R}^3</span> ",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527410,
              "key": "cfa76585-eaf1-4f4c-8cb5-3ffc302394ff",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "To prove that,  we will take a random vector   <span class=\"mathquill\">\n\\vec{v}=\\begin{bmatrix} \np\n\\\\q\n\\\\t\n\\end{bmatrix}</span> and show that it can be generated as a linear combination of of vectors   <span class=\"mathquill\">\n\\vec{v_1}, \\vec{v_2} </span> and  <span class=\"mathquill\">\n\\vec{v_3} </span>.",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527411,
              "key": "eb448c1d-b489-412c-a11f-6a8efaf975be",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "In a quick observation we can see that:\n\n <span class=\"mathquill\">\n\\vec{v}= p\\begin{bmatrix} \n1\n\\\\0\n\\\\0\n\\end{bmatrix}+q\\begin{bmatrix} \n0\n\\\\1\n\\\\0\n\\end{bmatrix}+t\\begin{bmatrix} \n0\n\\\\0\n\\\\1\n\\end{bmatrix}</span>\n\n\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": 527688,
          "key": "08359098-b7d4-44b4-9106-f11cab49eb35",
          "title": "Linear Combination -Quiz 1",
          "semantic_type": "Concept",
          "is_public": true,
          "user_state": {
            "node_key": "08359098-b7d4-44b4-9106-f11cab49eb35",
            "completed_at": null,
            "last_viewed_at": null,
            "unstructured": null
          },
          "resources": null,
          "atoms": [
            {
              "id": 527689,
              "key": "f259f983-b72a-4ad6-ad3e-9dbc2b140ebc",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "The following is a set of three vectors:\n\n(1) <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_1}=\\begin{bmatrix} 1\n\\\\ 2\n\\\\ 3\n\n\\end{bmatrix} </span> \n\n(2)\n  <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_2}=\\begin{bmatrix} 2\n\\\\ 2\n\\\\ 2\n\n\\end{bmatrix}</span>  \n\n(3)   <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_3}=\\begin{bmatrix} 8\n\\\\ 8\n\\\\ 8\n\n\\end{bmatrix}</span>\n\n\n All three vectors are  <span class=\"mathquill\">\\in\\mathbb{R^3}</span> \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527758,
              "key": "c4f2062d-be97-4297-b732-4d83ba788103",
              "title": "",
              "semantic_type": "CheckboxQuizAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "instructor_notes": null,
              "user_state": {
                "node_key": "c4f2062d-be97-4297-b732-4d83ba788103",
                "completed_at": null,
                "last_viewed_at": null,
                "unstructured": null
              },
              "question": {
                "prompt": "Which vectors above define a plane spanned by a linear combination?",
                "answers": [
                  {
                    "id": "a1517353378608",
                    "text": "(1), (2) and (3)",
                    "is_correct": false
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "a1517353569841",
                    "text": "(1) and (2)",
                    "is_correct": true
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "a1517353579493",
                    "text": "(1) and (3)",
                    "is_correct": true
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "a1517353587835",
                    "text": "(2) and (3)",
                    "is_correct": false
                  }
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": 527763,
              "key": "766d5218-482e-4e5d-afb4-ebb941ac1109",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "The question in this quiz may seem a bit strange. We have three vectors, why do they not all define the plane that can be spanned by a linear combination of them all?",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527766,
              "key": "f37b1b89-7247-4aa9-94cb-7fb2afc0dc64",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "A simple glance at vectors <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_2} </span>  and <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_3} </span> will show you that one vector can be defined as a linear combination of the other.\n\nfor example:\n\n<span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_2} =0.25\\vec{v_3}</span> \n\n<span class=\"mathquill\">\\begin{bmatrix} 2\n\\\\ 2\n\\\\ 2\n\n\\end{bmatrix}=0.25\\begin{bmatrix} 8\n\\\\ 8\n\\\\ 8\n\n\\end{bmatrix}</span> \n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527785,
              "key": "ec1e3650-b4d2-4dc8-bd42-e5fff4ee913f",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "In other words, if we use <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_2}</span> as a part of our linear combination (for creating finding the vectors spanned), we do not need <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_3}</span>. And vice versa: if we use <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_3}</span> as a part of our linear combination (for creating finding the vectors spanned), we do not need <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_2}</span>.\n\nTherefore, to define the plane spanned by a linear combination of the vectors above, we need (<span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_2}</span> and <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_1}</span>) or (<span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_3}</span> and <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_1}</span>).\n\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": 514145,
          "key": "fd7ae294-9671-4f53-88ef-230ec6913302",
          "title": "Linear Dependency ",
          "semantic_type": "Concept",
          "is_public": true,
          "user_state": {
            "node_key": "fd7ae294-9671-4f53-88ef-230ec6913302",
            "completed_at": null,
            "last_viewed_at": null,
            "unstructured": null
          },
          "resources": null,
          "atoms": [
            {
              "id": 518719,
              "key": "dddba4b2-2be1-406f-9db4-f97296ed01ae",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "# Linear Dependency ",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527794,
              "key": "2ff71931-7ae5-42c9-a407-1bec7ed31dbb",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "Lets look again at two of the vectors we saw in the previous quiz:\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527795,
              "key": "e7c73794-49dc-421a-8e33-ec5a005cff96",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "  - <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_2}=\\begin{bmatrix} 2\n\\\\ 2\n\\\\ 2\n\n\\end{bmatrix}</span>  \n\n- <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_3}=\\begin{bmatrix} 8\n\\\\ 8\n\\\\ 8\n\n\\end{bmatrix}</span>\n\nWe stated that one vector can be derived from the other by a simple mathematical linear combination. \n\nFor example:\n\n<span class=\"mathquill\">4\\vec{v_2} =\\vec{v_3}</span> \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527800,
              "key": "32122fba-37f3-4d1c-8075-96099495425e",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "When one vector **can** be defined as a linear combination of the other vectors, they are a set of  **linearly dependent** vectors.\n\nWhen each vector in a set of vectors  vector **can not** be defined as a linear combination of the other vectors, they are a set of  **linearly independent** vectors.\n\n\n\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527802,
              "key": "3747f707-9fc4-4917-a37b-df7382015a48",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "In our example, \n\n-  {<span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_2} </span>  , <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_3} </span>} is a linearly dependent set\n\n-  {<span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_1} </span>  , <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_2} </span>} is a linearly independent set\n\nand \n\n-  {<span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_1} </span>  , <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_3} </span>} is a linearly independent set\n\n(<span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{v_1} </span> is defined in the previous quiz as:  <span class=\"mathquill\">\\begin{bmatrix} 1\n\\\\ 2\n\\\\ 3\n\n\\end{bmatrix} </span> )\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527845,
              "key": "723c24df-43f0-40b3-b965-2d894aec4204",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "The easiest way to know if a set of vectors is linear dependent or not, is with the use of **determinants**.\nDeterminants are beyond the scope of our Linear Algebra Essentials and we will not focus on that. ",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": 520249,
          "key": "852f9480-8058-4f61-bdc3-194408b72d92",
          "title": "Solving a Simplified Set of Equations",
          "semantic_type": "Concept",
          "is_public": true,
          "user_state": {
            "node_key": "852f9480-8058-4f61-bdc3-194408b72d92",
            "completed_at": null,
            "last_viewed_at": null,
            "unstructured": null
          },
          "resources": null,
          "atoms": [
            {
              "id": 522144,
              "key": "13ba0d29-f861-475c-a8da-f79c2d8e55df",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "# Solving a Simplified Set of Equations",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 521424,
              "key": "33cdb1e3-c99a-4491-9bc1-95f73fe7bbfd",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "A linear combination of vector by scalars brings us to our next important topic:\n**A system of Linear Equations**.\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 521425,
              "key": "21e321fd-a9fc-42e8-a4ba-69cb7763cac5",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "In this Linear Algebra lesson we will dive only into a system of two linear equations with two unknowns.\n\n In a broader Linear Algebra class you will find [more information](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_of_linear_equations) about a system of  <span class=\"mathquill\">n</span> linear equations, where  <span class=\"mathquill\">n</span> can be any number.",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 521427,
              "key": "cb1b71eb-76ab-4183-81af-c51d148c5b3d",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "Assume that we have two vectors:\n\n- <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{x}=\\begin{bmatrix} \n-14\n\\\\2\n\n\\end{bmatrix}</span> \n\n\n-  <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{y}=\\begin{bmatrix} \n5\n\\\\-1\n\n\\end{bmatrix}</span> \n\nand we would like to represent a new vector: \n <span class=\"mathquill\">\\begin{bmatrix} \n-13\n\\\\3\n\n\\end{bmatrix}</span>  as a linear combination of  <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{x}</span> and \n<span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{y}</span>.\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 521426,
              "key": "0d489da0-7f02-4801-863c-08404cafee9e",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "In other words, we are looking for a two scalars, lets call them <span class=\"mathquill\">a</span> and <span class=\"mathquill\">b</span>, that will hold the following equation:",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 521428,
              "key": "ccd9966c-fc92-4aa1-b371-dfe705f9959f",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": " <span class=\"mathquill\">a\\begin{bmatrix} \n-14\n\\\\2\n\n\\end{bmatrix}+b\\begin{bmatrix} \n5\n\\\\-1\n\n\\end{bmatrix}=\\begin{bmatrix} \n-13\n\\\\3\n\n\\end{bmatrix}</span> \n\n_Equation  9_",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 521429,
              "key": "accbd635-239a-4911-9bcb-ff6f6482d5c5",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "We now know how to multiply a vector by a scalar, so lets do that:",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 521430,
              "key": "a4191532-0116-4101-89ed-2893af0c8d87",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": " <span class=\"mathquill\">\\begin{bmatrix} \n(-14)a\n\\\\2a\n\n\\end{bmatrix}+\\begin{bmatrix} \n5b\n\\\\(-1)b\n\n\\end{bmatrix}=\\begin{bmatrix} \n-13\n\\\\3\n\n\\end{bmatrix}</span> \n\n_Equation 10_",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 521432,
              "key": "847507f7-4306-47f2-97bc-9e2b6fb72b44",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "The equation above will give us two separate equations:\n \n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 522154,
              "key": "2c9e5af3-84d2-472f-88cd-9ad813292baf",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "ImageAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "url": "https://video.udacity-data.com/topher/2018/January/5a6c1979_screen-shot-2018-01-26-at-10.16.48-pm/screen-shot-2018-01-26-at-10.16.48-pm.png",
              "non_google_url": "https://s3.cn-north-1.amazonaws.com.cn/u-img/2c9e5af3-84d2-472f-88cd-9ad813292baf",
              "caption": "",
              "alt": "",
              "width": 200,
              "height": 100,
              "instructor_notes": null
            },
            {
              "id": 522152,
              "key": "77945131-9bc7-4b15-ba35-bee01d22c8d3",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "The Above set of equations is referred to in literature as a _set of two equations with two unknowns_.\n\nThis set can be solved using three theoretical methods:\n- Graphical method\n- Substitution method\n- Elimination method\n\nWe will go through all methods here.",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 522153,
              "key": "81426443-4b21-451b-ae39-b287616b111c",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "**Graphical solution:**\n\nDraw both lines (linear plots) and find the intersection.\n\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 522155,
              "key": "d44e6a95-1632-4302-9700-053cec5a6c64",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "The intersection is the solution to  <span class=\"mathquill\">(a,b)</span> as it is the only point on both lines. Or, in other words, it is the only point that satisfied both equations.\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 522159,
              "key": "9ec17a04-ae83-4e7f-9686-e68d5cb40a49",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "ImageAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "url": "https://video.udacity-data.com/topher/2018/January/5a6c24eb_screen-shot-2018-01-26-at-11.05.49-pm/screen-shot-2018-01-26-at-11.05.49-pm.png",
              "non_google_url": "https://s3.cn-north-1.amazonaws.com.cn/u-img/9ec17a04-ae83-4e7f-9686-e68d5cb40a49",
              "caption": "",
              "alt": "",
              "width": 300,
              "height": 300,
              "instructor_notes": null
            },
            {
              "id": 527305,
              "key": "c2afc0e6-52ad-43f6-bc4a-2b0c36f3c2b1",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "We can clearly see that:\n\n <span class=\"mathquill\">a= -0.5</span> \n\nand\n\n <span class=\"mathquill\">b= -4</span> ",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 522156,
              "key": "87890469-e993-45c0-a597-e1f9bf10bca0",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "**Substitution:**\n\nIsolate a variable from one of the equations and substitute it in the second. \n\nThis method will reduce our system of equations to a single equation with a single unknown.\n\nIn our example:",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 522157,
              "key": "ab0f4d2a-0a33-4bd7-9841-a8663d55d512",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": " (1) <span class=\"mathquill\">-14a+5b=-13</span> \n\n (2) <span class=\"mathquill\"> 2a-b=3</span> \n\n\nfrom (1) <span class=\"mathquill\">2a-b=3\\Rightarrow b=2a-3</span> \n\nSubstitute b in equation (2)\n\n <span class=\"mathquill\">-14a+5(2a-3)=-13</span>  and solve for  <span class=\"mathquill\">a</span> .\n\nSimple algebra will result in  <span class=\"mathquill\">a=-0.5</span>\n\n\nSubstitute <span class=\"mathquill\">a</span> in equation (1) or (2) above and you will find that <span class=\"mathquill\">b=-4</span>.\n\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 522160,
              "key": "0964f1c2-0dc0-4b8e-a5cd-b4810b01bb3f",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "**Elimination:**\n\nIn this method we will eliminate one of the variables, by enforcing the same absolute value to one of the scalars (or coefficients) . \n\nLet's look at the equations again:",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 522161,
              "key": "e5f52b20-a0ea-4391-b2f6-d82b3664ab4a",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "ImageAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "url": "https://video.udacity-data.com/topher/2018/January/5a6c27fb_screen-shot-2018-01-26-at-11.16.45-pm/screen-shot-2018-01-26-at-11.16.45-pm.png",
              "non_google_url": "https://s3.cn-north-1.amazonaws.com.cn/u-img/e5f52b20-a0ea-4391-b2f6-d82b3664ab4a",
              "caption": "",
              "alt": "",
              "width": 200,
              "height": 100,
              "instructor_notes": null
            },
            {
              "id": 522162,
              "key": "ebde17bd-17a7-49cb-bb03-b1c5080eb4de",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "If we multiply equation 2 by 5 we will have the following set of equations: ",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 522164,
              "key": "7a15e7b5-c34e-434d-be7b-83eb37cd382d",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "ImageAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "url": "https://video.udacity-data.com/topher/2018/January/5a6c28b0_screen-shot-2018-01-26-at-11.21.42-pm/screen-shot-2018-01-26-at-11.21.42-pm.png",
              "non_google_url": "https://s3.cn-north-1.amazonaws.com.cn/u-img/7a15e7b5-c34e-434d-be7b-83eb37cd382d",
              "caption": "",
              "alt": "",
              "width": 200,
              "height": 100,
              "instructor_notes": null
            },
            {
              "id": 527307,
              "key": "787aca84-caa7-43bb-8843-e7b46e6c0c4e",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "(Notice the the absolute value of the scalar multiplying  <span class=\"mathquill\">b</span>, the coefficient of <span class=\"mathquill\">b</span>, is 5 on both equations).",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 522171,
              "key": "e59a4497-06da-4c76-833d-fecd01da46f1",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "Now let's add them up.\n\nWe will have the following single equation with a single unknown:\n\n<span class=\"mathquill\">-4a+0b=2</span> \n\nor:\n\n<span class=\"mathquill\">-4a=2\\Rightarrow a=-0.5</span> \n\nSubstitute <span class=\"mathquill\">a</span> in any of the equations and you will find that <span class=\"mathquill\">b=-4</span>.\n\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 522183,
              "key": "6b36d03f-25e9-4782-b70a-efed98b9796d",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "Final answer:\n\nWe found scalars <span class=\"mathquill\">a</span> and <span class=\"mathquill\">b</span> that represent vector  \n <span class=\"mathquill\">\\begin{bmatrix} \n-13\n\\\\3\n\n\\end{bmatrix}</span>  as a linear combination of  <span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{x}</span> and \n<span class=\"mathquill\">\\vec{y}</span>. \n\n\n <span class=\"mathquill\">a\\begin{bmatrix} \n-14\n\\\\2\n\n\\end{bmatrix}+b\\begin{bmatrix} \n5\n\\\\-1\n\n\\end{bmatrix}=\\begin{bmatrix} \n-13\n\\\\3\n\n\\end{bmatrix}</span> \n\nThe single solution is:\n\n<span class=\"mathquill\">a=-0.5</span> and\n<span class=\"mathquill\">b=-4</span>",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 527313,
              "key": "208c1b0c-4cc4-4037-932b-92c3f5bf7ad5",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "In this example, one coefficient was positive and the other was negative. Ask yourself, what would you have done if they were both positive, or both negative?\n\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 522184,
              "key": "d0d8af37-1549-4a40-b1cc-2fd8e777d168",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "Let's think about another question:\n\nWill a set of two linear equations with two unknowns always have a solution? And if so, will it always be a single solution?\n\nThe next set of quizzes will help us answer this question.\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": 514146,
          "key": "f6f8dcbc-04e2-432e-b3ff-5194a4cc239e",
          "title": "Linear Combination - Quiz 2",
          "semantic_type": "Concept",
          "is_public": true,
          "user_state": {
            "node_key": "f6f8dcbc-04e2-432e-b3ff-5194a4cc239e",
            "completed_at": null,
            "last_viewed_at": null,
            "unstructured": null
          },
          "resources": null,
          "atoms": [
            {
              "id": 522192,
              "key": "279ca850-fe8f-439f-b48b-96aa19d8dcc4",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "# Linear Combination - Quiz 2",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 522186,
              "key": "42ed4fae-051d-4ab8-8739-ec35f183015e",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "Let's think about the following question:\n\nWill a set of two linear equations with two unknowns always have a solution? And if so, will it always be a single solution?\n",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 522187,
              "key": "a7f5a620-6582-4b17-b85c-bad3d0632299",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "Consider the following set of equations:",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 522188,
              "key": "4a7ee533-a884-41e4-8848-ae90ab18dbf2",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "ImageAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "url": "https://video.udacity-data.com/topher/2018/January/5a6c2ec9_screen-shot-2018-01-26-at-11.48.02-pm/screen-shot-2018-01-26-at-11.48.02-pm.png",
              "non_google_url": "https://s3.cn-north-1.amazonaws.com.cn/u-img/4a7ee533-a884-41e4-8848-ae90ab18dbf2",
              "caption": "",
              "alt": "",
              "width": 200,
              "height": 100,
              "instructor_notes": null
            },
            {
              "id": 522189,
              "key": "c19d6bfb-d0b9-46cf-b7bc-0348d2f6e4fa",
              "title": "What is the solution for a and b?",
              "semantic_type": "RadioQuizAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "instructor_notes": null,
              "user_state": {
                "node_key": "c19d6bfb-d0b9-46cf-b7bc-0348d2f6e4fa",
                "completed_at": null,
                "last_viewed_at": null,
                "unstructured": null
              },
              "question": {
                "prompt": "What is the solution for a and b?",
                "answers": [
                  {
                    "id": "a1517039353680",
                    "text": "a=0, b=2",
                    "is_correct": false
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "a1517039391675",
                    "text": "a=2, b=0",
                    "is_correct": false
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "a1517039404483",
                    "text": "There are no solutions",
                    "is_correct": false
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "a1517039415415",
                    "text": "There are infinite  number of solutions",
                    "is_correct": true
                  }
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": 522190,
              "key": "786d2a65-4536-438f-8f35-b70e6523555a",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "TextAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "text": "The two equations here are **linearly dependent**.\n\nTry to sketch them graphically. What do you see? How may points of intersection are there?\n\nSince the two equations are linearly dependent, graphically they define the same line. Hence there are infinite number of solutions to the set of these equations. Basically, each point on the line (depicted by the blue x) satisfies the equation.  ",
              "instructor_notes": ""
            },
            {
              "id": 578202,
              "key": "ea564847-f116-4ba1-949a-3b75154843b4",
              "title": null,
              "semantic_type": "ImageAtom",
              "is_public": true,
              "url": "https://video.udacity-data.com/topher/2018/March/5abc28f4_screen-shot-2018-03-28-at-4.44.34-pm/screen-shot-2018-03-28-at-4.44.34-pm.png",
              "non_google_url": "https://s3.cn-north-1.amazonaws.com.cn/u-img/ea564847-f116-4ba1-949a-3b75154843b4",
              "caption": "",
              "alt": "",
              "width": 400,
              "height": 300,
              "instructor_notes": null
            }
          ]
        },
